sec.title:
Soil splash via rain or irrigation (i.e., loss from soil) (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{R}_{splash}}_{t}, {{I}_{splash}}_{t}$$\end{document})

sec.p:
The effect of irrigation and rain splash in the field was based on the QMRA model developed by Allende et al.27. Accordingly, splash of soil (and ECO157) to romaine would be facilitated either via irrigation water on a sunny day or rainwater on a rainy day. The maximum quantity of soil splashed by rain was assumed to be equal to that splashed by overhead spray irrigation. However, the quantity of soil splashed by rain was also proportional to the standardized monthly precipitation level (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${Prec}_{nor{m}_{m}}$$\end{document}), reflecting the intensity of rain. We assumed that the quantity of soil splashed on sunny days varied by different irrigation systems, with overhead spray irrigation had the potential of causing the most amount soil to splash and drip irrigation causing the least (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${M}_{irr}$$\end{document}). The amount of soil splashed during irrigation was also affected by the intensity of irrigation systems, where each system assumed to mimic an intermediate rainfall, equal to the median of the standardized precipitation \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left(Pre{c}_{nor{m}_{m}}\right)$$\end{document}. In case of a splash, a fraction of ECO157 in soil would transfer onto the romaine (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$LsR$$\end{document} during rain or \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$LsI$$\end{document} during irrigation, Supplementary Table S4) via transfer of contaminated soil75. The terms for modeling rain (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{R}_{splash}}_{t}$$\end{document}) and irrigation splash (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${{I}_{splash}}_{t}$$\end{document}) in the model (1)–(6) were derived as shown in Supplementary Table S5.

Daily inactivation of persister and non-persister cells in soil was constant. We used four different decay rates to represent non-persister36,61 and persisters’62 decay in BSAAO-amended soil and soil with no BSAAO application. We used slower inactivation in BSAAO amended soil (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${R}_{dman}$$\end{document} for non-persisters and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${R}_{dma{n}_{P}}$$\end{document} for persisters) and faster inactivation in soil with no BSAAO application (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${R}_{ds}$$\end{document} for non-persisters and \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${R}_{d{s}_{P}}$$\end{document} for persisters). Persister cells decayed at a rate 10 times slower than that of their non-persister counterparts, based on the decay curve provided in Chen (2020) for ECO157 persisters in soil62. Decay parameters in soil (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$SNdeca{y}_{t}, SPdeca{y}_{t}$$\end{document}) in the model (1)–(6) are explained in Supplementary Table S5.

A small fraction of non-persister ECO157 cells were transitioned to persister cells on each day in soil47,76,77. Persisters coexisted with non-persisters and comprised up to 0.01% of the population in soil environments76,77. The cells could also switch between the persister and non-persister states78. Although the characteristics and the formation mechanisms of persisters are complex78, our model focused only on their enhanced ability to survive, which facilitated modeling biphasic decay. While the direct estimates for the switch rates in BSAAO-amended soil were unavailable, we used the study by Hofstrenge et al.77, which indicated a strong one-to-one correlation between switch rates (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Nto{P}_{man},Nto{P}_{S}$$\end{document}) and the fraction of persisters (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${Pmax}_{man},{Pmax}_{S}$$\end{document}). We assumed that the persister state was more prevalent in BSAAO-amended soil batches (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Nto{P}_{man}$$\end{document}). This assumption was based on the observation that pathogens regrew and recovered to a culturable state months after being introduced into soils through dairy BSAAO application79. This delayed recovery might suggest the initial presence of persister cells within the BSAAO that was applied on the field80. Details on the switch terms (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$SNtoS{P}_{t}$$\end{document}) in the model (1)–(6) are provided in Supplementary Table S5.

Given the rapid decay of ECO157 on field romaine27,39,81, we assumed that the initial ECO157 count on the field romaine was negligible one day prior to the start of the 14-day countdown period (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${C}_{{L}_{0}}=0$$\end{document}). However, the sensitivity of model predictions to this assumption was tested in scenario analysis (see Supplementary Table S7).

Contamination of romaine through irrigation followed a similar mechanism to that described for soil contamination. The volume of irrigation water captured by the romaine batches \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\left({v}_{irr}\right)$$\end{document} transferred a fraction of ECO157 cells from water to the romaine plants (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$T{r}_{ecirr}$$\end{document}). The total volume of water delivered to the batch area (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
